	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Well, I don't understand why you're still asking questions so. Yeah, the vertical and horizontal mirroring means that the duplicating of the nametables themselves are done vertically or horizontally, respectively. It would seems more logical to call them on the opposite way, like on the solver pads where there is hardwired mirroring.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Memblers</b> [ Sat Aug 20, 2005 8:36 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Roth wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Now, I noticed that the nametable at $2000 and $2800 (like in Membler's post on the other thread), as well as $2400 and $2C00(?) are the exact same.  Why is this?<br /></div>
<br />
<br />It's because the NES has only enough VRAM for 2 nametables, but there's enough address space for 4.  They made it so you can select on the cartridge which 2 tables are usable (and which 2 tables are mirrored) by connecting a couple pins together on the cart.
<br />
<br />It's pretty much there so you can choose between scrolling horizontally or vertically without having partially-drawn parts of the nametable on-screen.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


